Measuring Apical Constriction

David Kleinhans

2017-11-11

1 Introduction

1.1 Apical Constriction

During development and cellular differentiation cells undergo drastic shape changes from one morphological typus to another, known as morphogenesis. Collective cellular morphologies give rise to tissue morphology, which gives rise to organ morphology and so on. One distinct morphogenetic feature is apical constriction (AC), an active narrowing of cellular apices. Apical constriction occurs in all multicellular organisms and most often during early embryogenesis [1] e.g.during

  • C.elegans gastrulation [2]
  • D.Melanogaster & Vertebrate neural tube formation
  • Epithelial-to-mesenchymal transition and ingression

A principal definition is given by J.y. Lee and R.M.Harland [2] and illustrated in figure 1.

Apical constriction is the process in which contraction of the apical side of a cell causes the cell to take on a wedged shape. Generally, this shape change is coordinated across many cells of an epithelial layer, generating forces that can bend or fold the cell sheet.

Figure 1: Apical constriction and tissue bending. a D. Melanogaster Mesoderm invagination. b Vertebrate neurulation. c and d schematic representation of AC in an epithelial tissue. e Molecular pathways model for vertebrates and invertebrates. f Function of RhoGEF2 in AC [3].

1.2 Measuring AC

Before measuring apical constriction, one has to define it first

  • AC is independent of orientation and polarization
    • Cells can be dorso-ventral (DV) polarized
    • Cells can also be cranial-caudal (CC) polarized
    • Cells can be radially polarized [4]
  • AC is independent of lateral height
    • Lateral height can be described as the distance of the two farthest points of the surface area of a cell
    • also known as feret
    • Two cells with different lateral heights can be equally apically constricted
  • AC is independent of cell height
    • In an horizontally aligned tissue, cell height is the difference between the maximum and minimum position in Z
  • AC is independent of cell volume / size
    • The volume of a cell is its size
    • Two cells of different size can be equally apically constricted

1.2.1 Apical Constriction Index

An application for the apical constriction index (ACI) for the cells in the lateral line primordium was in a study from 2012 where it was shown that Fgfr-Ras-MAPK signaling is required for AC and Rock2a localization [5,6].

Figure 2: Apical constriction index. (A) 3D reconstructed cells of a DMSO control primordium and (B) 3D reconstructed cells of a primordium deficient of Fgf signaling.

While trying to reproduce these results we figured two principal weaknesses of applying this measurement to the cells of the lateral line primordium. Those are * It does not respect that apical constriction is independent of lateral height * It does not differenciate between dorso-ventral and cranial-caudal tissue polarization

library(plyr)
library(dplyr)
read.data.all.3D <- function(file){
    dat <- read.table(file, sep="\t", header=TRUE)
    dat$Nb <- NULL
    dat$Obj <- file
    dat$X <- NULL
    Zcal <- dat$CZ..unit./dat$CZ..pix.                # To transform pix to unit value in Z
    XYcal <- dat$CX..unit./dat$CX..pix.               # To transform pix to unit value in X and Y
    dat$Height <- (dat$Zmax..pix.-dat$Zmin..pix.)*Zcal  # calculate Height and transform to unit value
    dat$Height <- dat$Height*Zcal                       # calculate Height and transform to unit value
    dat$Length <- (dat$Xmax..pix.-dat$Xmin..pix.)*XYcal # calculate Length and transform to unit value
    dat$Width <- (dat$Ymax..pix.-dat$Ymin..pix.)*XYcal  # calculate Width and transform to unit value
    dat$HF <- dat$Height/dat$Feret..unit.               # calculate Height/Feret ratio
    # calculate Phi
    dat$Phi <- ((atan(dat$Height/dat$Feret..unit.))*180)/pi
    adj <- dat$Length/2
    opp <- dat$Height
    hyp <- dat$Feret..unit.
    dat$Phi <- ((atan(adj/opp))*180)/pi
    #dat$Phi <- ((asin(1/hyp))*180)/pi
    #dat$ACPhi <- 180-((((atan(dat$Height/dat$Feret..unit.))*180)/pi)+90) # <- ACPhi3
    dat$ACPhi <- 180-((((atan(adj/opp))*180)/pi)+90)  #                     <- ACPhi2
    #dat$ACPhi <- asin(dat$Height/dat$Feret..unit.)    #                    <- ACPhi1
    trail <- ((max(dat$CX..pix.)-min(dat$CX..pix.))*XYcal[1])*0.25
    dat$CXN <- (max(dat$CX..pix.)-dat$CX..pix.)*XYcal   # normalize CX against leading edge
    #dat <- subset(dat, dat$CXN < quantile(dat$CXN, 0.99, na.rm=TRUE) & dat$CXN > quantile(dat$CXN, 0.01, na.rm=TRUE))
    #lower <- subset(dat, dat$CXN > quantile(dat$CXN, 0.99, na.rm=TRUE))
    #print(lower$Label)
    #upper <- subset(dat, dat$CXN < quantile(dat$CXN, 0.01, na.rm=TRUE))
    #print(upper$Label)
    #trail <- quantile(dat$CXN, 0.2, na.rm=TRUE)
    print(trail)
    dat$FLsplit <- cut(dat$CXN, breaks = c(-Inf, trail, Inf), labels = c("leading", "trailing"))
    dat$SAV <- dat$Surf..unit./dat$Vol..unit.           # calculate Surface Area to Volume ratio 
    dat$VolN <- (1/min(dat$Vol..unit., na.rm=TRUE))*dat$Vol..unit.  # normalize Volumes
    dat$GT <- GT                                        # add Genotype
    dat$CZ..pix. <- NULL
    dat$CX..pix. <- NULL
    dat$CY..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Xmin..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Xmax..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Ymin..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Ymax..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Zmin..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Zmax..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Vol..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Surf..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Spher..pix. <- NULL
    dat$Comp..pix. <- NULL
    return(dat)
  }
read.data.all.ACI <- function(file){
    dat <- read.table(file, header=TRUE)
    dat$objlabelArray <- NULL
    dat$ACI <- dat$basalArray/dat$apicalArray
    return(dat)
  }
